Introduction :

As crime rate in chicago observed more than aversgae as compared to other states in US.In our project we are focusing to find the areas least in crime rates which could be reffered while purchasing a house in chicago city.The analysis is based on community areas,districts, arrest rates and crime counts.

Research objectives:

1 To find top 10 crime types. 2 Least 3 community areas in crime count. 3 Analysis on trend change in year vs.community areas. 4 To find top and least 5 districts according to arrest rates. 5 Evaluate districts with maximum and minimum crime count . - To find location description where crime has occured in least 2 crime count districts. - To find Primary crime type on location description types

Dataset information

The data is taken from Chicago data portal on public safety. https://data.cityofchicago.org/Public-Safety/Crimes-2001-to-present/ijzp-q8t2 This project deals with the crime rate in Chicago from 2001 to present.The data containes millions of entries and spread over 22 variables.

Explorating the Dataset

Dimensions of dataset:

crimeData = read.csv("/Users/vineethmenon/Desktop/UCSC/Data Analytics/Crimes_-_2001_to_present.csv")
dim(crimeData)
## [1] 6548274      22

Data Description :

  1. ID - Unique identifier for the record.
  2. Case Number - The Chicago Police Department RD Number (Records Division Number), which is unique to the incident.
  3. Date - Date when the incident occurred. this is sometimes a best estimate.
  4. Block - The partially redacted address where the incident occurred, placing it on the same block as the actual address.
  5. IUCR - The Illinois Unifrom Crime Reporting code. This is directly linked to the Primary Type and Description.
  6. Primary Type - The primary description of the IUCR code.
  7. Description - The secondary description of the IUCR code, a subcategory of the primary description.
  8. Location Description - Description of the location where the incident occurred.
  9. Arrest - Indicates whether an arrest was made.
  10. Domestic - Indicates whether the incident was domestic-related as defined by the Illinois Domestic Violence Act.
  11. Beat - Indicates the beat where the incident occurred. A beat is the smallest police geographic area - each beat has a dedicated police beat car. Three to five beats make up a police sector, and three sectors make up a police district.
  12. District - Indicates the police district where the incident occurred.
  13. Ward - The ward (City Council district) where the incident occurred.
  14. Community Area - Indicates the community area where the incident occurred. Chicago has 77 community areas.
  15. FBI Code - Indicates the crime classification as outlined in the FBIs National Incident-Based Reporting System (NIBRS).
  16. X Coordinate - The x coordinate of the location where the incident occurred in State Plane Illinois East NAD 1983 projection. This location is shifted from the actual location for partial redaction but falls on the same block.
  17. Y Coordinate - The y coordinate of the location where the incident occurred in State Plane Illinois East NAD 1983 projection. This location is shifted from the actual location for partial redaction but falls on the same block.
  18. Year - Year the incident occurred.
  19. Updated On - Date and time the record was last updated.
  20. Latitude - The latitude of the location where the incident occurred. This location is shifted from the actual location for partial redaction but falls on the same block.
  21. Longitude - The longitude of the location where the incident occurred. This location is shifted from the actual location for partial redaction but falls on the same block.
  22. Location - The location where the incident occurred in a format that allows for creation of maps and other geographic operations on this data portal. This location is shifted from the actual location for partial redaction but falls on the same block.

Data preprocessing

  • Focussing analysis on subset of data. As per the plots, it is infered that there is reduction in crime over the years. With huge data available from 2001 to 2018, we are subsetting the data to focus our analysis on recent 10yrs, that is from 2008.
recentData <- subset(crimeData, subset = crimeData$Year > 2007)
recentCrimeData <- recentData
RecentData1<-recentData
Recent1 <- recentData
hist(recentData$Year, breaks = 100)

Top 10 crime types from 2008-2018

Calculated the total yearly occurrence for each crime type and the average total occurrence per year for each crime type over 2001-2018

recentData<-cbind(recentData,quantity=seq(1,1,nrow(crimeData)))
AggrCrime<- aggregate(quantity~Year+Primary.Type,data=recentData,FUN=sum)
AggCrime1<- aggregate(quantity~Primary.Type, data=AggrCrime,FUN=mean)
AggCrime2<- AggCrime1[order(AggCrime1$quantity,decreasing=TRUE),]
top10 <- AggCrime2[1:10,]

BarGraph to represent the Top least Dangerous Community Areas

areadata <- recentData[which(recentData$Community.Area != ""),]
aggdata_area <- aggregate(quantity~Year+Community.Area,data=areadata,FUN=sum)
aggdata_area2 <- aggregate(quantity~Community.Area,data=aggdata_area,FUN=sum)
aggdata_area2 <- aggdata_area2[order(aggdata_area2$quantity,decreasing=FALSE),]
least3_area <- aggdata_area2[2:4,]
with(least3_area,barplot(least3_area$quantity,col=c("violet","purple","blue","green","yellow","orange","red","lightblue","mistyrose","lightcyan"),main="The top least dangerous community areas in Chicago", xlab="Community area",ylab="Total crime occurrence from 2001-2014"))
legend("topright",lty="solid",col=c("violet","purple","blue","green","yellow","orange","red","lightblue","mistyrose","lightcyan"),legend=least3_area$Community.Area)

Analyze the change in occurence of crimes for the top three least dangerous community areas

least_area <- aggdata_area2[2:4,]
subaggdata_area2 <- aggdata_area[which(aggdata_area$Community.Area %in% least_area$Community.Area),]

ggplot(data=subaggdata_area2,aes(x=Year,y=quantity)) + facet_grid(.~Community.Area) + geom_point(aes(size=2,col=quantity)) + geom_line(aes(group=1, col=quantity)) + ggtitle("Change of the least 3 dangerous communities") + xlab("Year") + ylab("Total Occurrence")

Conclusion

According to the above analysis on Community areas, Arrest counts and District, we conclude the project based on individual analysis as follows : 1. Community Areas : On the basis of analysis community areas and crime counts 9, 47 and 12 have the least crime occurance. 2. Arrest : Evaluating the arrest count, District 11 has maximum arrest rate, and District 8 has the least. 3. Districts : Analysing the crime count in each district, District 31 has the least crime count and District 8 has the most. In further evaluting the location type the crime occured in District 31 is STREET.

On the above results, District 31, Community area 9 are safe for residing and based on the Arrest count and high crime count in District, District 8 is most unsafe to reside.
